<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  IMUMenuBar entitlements.

  This file is intentionally minimal.

  Notarization (issue #20) requires the binary to be signed with the Hardened
  Runtime enabled. That's a codesign flag (`--options=runtime`), not an
  entitlements key — so this file can be empty as far as Hardened Runtime is
  concerned and signing still works end-to-end.

  We deliberately do NOT enable App Sandbox (`com.apple.security.app-sandbox`)
  here. Three reasons:

  1. The GUI reads recovery archives from arbitrary paths under
     `~/Library/Application Support/imessage-unsent/archives/<id>/`
     (see RecoveryDetailLoader from #49). Sandboxing would block that read
     unless we either move archives inside the GUI's container (different
     permission model than the daemon writes today) or pair every read with
     a security-scoped bookmark dance. Out of scope for this PR.

  2. The Contacts integration (CNContactStore in #49) currently relies on
     the unsandboxed flow (NSContactsUsageDescription + runtime
     authorization). Sandboxing it would also need
     `com.apple.security.personal-information.addressbook` AND a re-test of
     the permission prompt UX. Out of scope for this PR.

  3. The webhook posting from the daemon side already lives in a separate
     LaunchAgent process — sandboxing the GUI does not constrain the daemon.

  Sandboxing remains a desirable end state and should land as its own PR
  once #49's archive-read and Contacts-access patterns have been adapted to
  the sandbox file-access rules.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
</dict>
</plist>
